<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="362" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,1808,1944]" pageId="4" pageNumber="362">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,470,1844,1871]" pageId="4" pageNumber="362">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among Ecuadorian species, recognized by the combination of small size (ca. 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="4" pageNumber="362" unit="mm" value="2.54">2.54 mm</quantity>
), the shallow pronotal impressions, the wide elytra with arcuate lateral margins and large serial punctures, and the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[366,435,1917,1943]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1617,1642]" captionTargetBox="[186,1411,197,1556]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1435,166,1598]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Hydrochus latipennis n. sp., habitus and male genitalia of holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3889416" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3889416/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="362">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
; described below).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3889414" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3889414" box="[151,955,1671,1696]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3889414/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="363" startId="5.[151,250,1671,1696]" targetBox="[191,1423,216,1604]" targetPageId="5">
